Cook,<br>
     The best advice I ever got as a Lieutenant was to listen well to my sergeant.  As for the old lance corporal, I probably would have said something, but getting all over his case would not have been my style.  I was admonished several times in 3 1/2 years not to be so informal with the enlisted men and to preserve some distance between us.  Paul Sutton, the agent orange expert from New Jersey, knew me for 2 years before he found out I had been an officer, and didn't want to believe it because I didn't seem the type to him.<br><br>
See also under the new REMF thread.<br><br>
Your mentioning of camouflaged shorts reminds me of how my wife of 6 weeks burned all my olive drab underwear when I separated from service.  As an Army brat (both my inlaws were ex-sergeants), she was glad to be parted from the military.  Little did both of us know I would wind up working for the Navy as a civilian for 25 years.
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


